Technical Alignment: 4D GSPT-SBL Model Specifications

1. Formal 4D State Vector and Governing Equations

The 4D GSPT-SBL model is defined as a mathematically closed, fast-slow dynamical system. The state vector \mathbf{x} = (e, U, V, T_s) \in \mathbb{R}^4 maps the turbulent kinetic energy to the macroscale environmental state.

* Fast Turbulent Coordinate:
  * e: Turbulent Kinetic Energy (TKE) [m^2 s^{-2}].
* Slow Environmental Coordinates:
  * U, V: Horizontal momentum components [m s^{-1}].
  * T_s: Surface skin temperature [K].

The system is partitioned by the singular perturbation parameter \varepsilon (0 < \varepsilon \ll 1), representing the separation between rapid turbulent adjustment and slow thermodynamic forcing.

Fast Subsystem (Turbulence Mechanics)

The evolution of e is governed by an energy-conserving fast field that utilizes a background mixing floor \delta to ensure the vector field remains C^\infty at the laminar transition:

\varepsilon \frac{de}{dt} = \mathcal{F}(e,U,V,T_s)

\mathcal{F}(e,U,V,T_s) = \sqrt{e + \delta} \left[ \eta\,\gamma\,(U^2 + V^2) - K \cdot G(T_s) \right] - \frac{(e+\delta)^{3/2}}{l_0}

Slow Subsystem (Atmospheric Rotational Dynamics & Surface Thermodynamics)

The horizontal momentum equations incorporate the Coriolis parameter f and geostrophic targets \mathbf{v}_g = (U_g, V_g). The friction term is unified via the regularized turbulent velocity scale u_* \sim \sqrt{e + \delta}: \frac{dU}{dt} = f(V - V_g) - \gamma \sqrt{e + \delta} \cdot U \frac{dV}{dt} = -f(U - U_g) - \gamma \sqrt{e + \delta} \cdot V

The thermal evolution of the surface is governed by the non-linear Surface Energy Budget (SEB): \frac{dT_s}{dt} = \frac{1}{C_{\text{skin}}} \left[ R_{\downarrow} - \sigma_{SB} T_s^4 - \lambda \frac{T_s - T_{\text{deep}}}{d_{\text{soil}}} - \rho c_p C_H \sqrt{e + \delta} \cdot (T_s - T_a) \right]

